In article <1993Feb9.191702.6416@ulysses.att.com> smb@research.att.com (Steven Bellovin) writes:
>Most folks recommend triple encryption, with
>two keys, and the second step a decryption using the second key.  The
>first and third steps use the first key.

 --and there are some of us who recommend triple encryption, with three
keys.

	The original proposal:

	encr(k1, decr(k2, encr(k1, x ) ) )

allows a hardware configuration to be configured to be compatible with
single stage des (by setting k1 = k2).

So does:

	encr(k3, decr(k2, encr(k1, x ) ) )

The only advantage I see for the original "triple" proposal was that it
saved on key bits -- but to my mind, that is the wrong thing to save.


